{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487362"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:07:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:07:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"331"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/331"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.09,0.06,0.02,0.69]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105747"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/331"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88214"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"337"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5695"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"868"},{"type":"contributions","id":"870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1501"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37794"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47980"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105747"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man develops a right lower lobe pneumonia. He has been nursed by his wife and son at home following a stroke six months ago which left him aphasic, densely hemiparetic on the right, and wheelchair-bound. When examined by the general practitioner in the patient\u0027s home, the man is cyanosed, agitated and only semi-rousable. There is an Advance Care Directive, in which the wife is appointed the Substitute decision-maker. His wife wants to continue caring for him at home, and for him not to receive any life-prolonging interventions as she believes this is what he would have wanted. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange for home oxygen","Transfer the patient to hospital","Seek opinion of a general physician","Seek the son\u0027s opinion","Respect the decision of the Substitute Decision Maker"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of issues to be addressed before answering this question. Firstly, does the patient have capacity to make a decision regarding their care? This is determined by their ability to understand and retain information including pros/cons, and be able to communicate this. Just because of the aphasia and this patient\u0027s inability to communicate by speech does not indicate that he lacks capacity. Secondly, determining who can make their decision. The patient has an Advance Care Directive (ACD) and this states that the wife is the Substitute Decision Maker (SDM) - this is in effect during periods of impaired decision-making capacity. Furthermore, his wife has a \u003Cem\u003Eclose and continuing\u003C/em\u003E relationship to him meaning she is a suitable person to make decisions on his behalf even in the absence of an ACD. The role of an SDM is to make decisions in accordance with what they think their loved one would have wanted or as documented in the ACD, rather than based on their own preference.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThus with a holistic approach to the patient, \u003Cstrong\u003Erespecting the decision of the Substitute Decision Maker\u003C/strong\u003E is the most reasonable action the doctor can take as well.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An Advance Care Directive appoints a Substitute Decision Maker who makes decisions based on the patient\u0027s previously expressed wishes, not their own preferences.","The Substitute Decision Maker must act in accordance with what the patient would have wanted, or what is documented in the ACD, not what they personally want.","When a patient lacks capacity, healthcare decisions should be guided by a valid Advance Care Directive and the appointed Substitute Decision Maker."],"references":["Advance care directive. Canberra, ACT; 2019 July 17 [cited 2020 Dec 20]. Available: https://www.health.gov.au/health-topics/palliative-care/planning-your-palliative-care/advance-care-directive","Advance Care Directive Factsheet. SA Health. Available at:\u003Chttps://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/045059804459d8048921ab76d172935c/ACD+Fact+Sheet+PC+20140613.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026amp;CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-045059804459d8048921ab76d172935c-nKKk4uZ\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88214"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"331"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88214"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-12T21:46:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-12T21:49:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"331"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105747"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"